<h1>
Understanding why adults abuse
animals: New developments in
theory and evidence-based
practice
</h1>

<h3> Thursday, July 1, 09:30-10:45</h3>
<br>
<h4>
Chair: Emma Alleyne (University of Kent)
</h4>
<br>
<h3>
Symposium Abstract 
</h3>
<p>
One of the most acute and distressing animal welfare problems is abuse
carried out by adults. There are difficulties to detect, intervene, and prevent
animal cruelty incidents due to the very nature of animals as
‘voiceless victims’. As a result, even when complaints are made,
convictions are rare and we are left with a limited evidence base to inform
practice. Despite these challenges, there is a growing field of research to
develop a greater understanding of the factors associated with animal
abuse, the mechanisms underpinning this behaviour, and effective
intervention strategies across disciplines. The aim of this symposium is
two-fold: (1) to present the latest developments in research and
methodology examining psychological mechanisms that support animal
abuse attitudes; and (2) to present applied perspectives that inform various
approaches to interventions.
</p>

<h5>Presentation 1: Empathy and Aggression Towards Animals
</h5>

<p>
Author:
Emma Alleyne &amp; Tom Denson <br>
Speaker: Emma Alleyne
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Animal abuse is a prevalent, yet understudied, form of aggression.
Although we have a good understanding of why adults are violent towards
each other, little research exists on why they engage in animal abuse.
Therefore, we currently depend on theories from interpersonal violence for
understanding human-animal aggression, which leaves us with open
questions regarding animal-oriented factors that enable this behaviour. The
role of empathy in the broader forensic psychological literature has been
evidenced as criminogenic and worthy of clinical attention. The aim of this
presentation is to explore how empathy facilitates aggression towards
animals. Further, we will examine, using experimental methods, if empathy
is a suitable target to reduce propensity to engage in animal abuse.
</p>
